1
00:02:24,440 --> 00:02:25,839
(He laughs)

2
00:02:42,400 --> 00:02:44,277
Ha, ha! I won.

3
00:02:45,440 --> 00:02:47,829
21...

4
00:02:47,880 --> 00:02:49,552
to 19.

5
00:02:49,600 --> 00:02:52,433
Three games out of four.

6
00:02:53,840 --> 00:02:55,432
What do I get?

7
00:02:56,720 --> 00:02:58,472
The boot?

8
00:02:58,520 --> 00:03:00,192
That's right.

9
00:03:01,560 --> 00:03:02,754
No!

10
00:03:02,800 --> 00:03:03,994
(Screams)

11
00:03:06,680 --> 00:03:08,079
(Laughs)

12
00:03:08,120 --> 00:03:09,633
(Screams)

13
00:03:12,280 --> 00:03:13,429
No!

14
00:03:13,480 --> 00:03:15,471
(Loud rock music)

15
00:03:22,960 --> 00:03:24,757
Turn it down.

16
00:03:27,280 --> 00:03:29,430
Christ! It's bloody freezing!

17
00:03:33,360 --> 00:03:34,998
It's bloody Arctic!

18
00:03:35,040 --> 00:03:36,951
If you insist on going around naked...

19
00:03:38,200 --> 00:03:40,509
What are you wearing tonight?
Cloak and dagger?

20
00:03:40,560 --> 00:03:42,278
What would you suggest?

21
00:03:42,320 --> 00:03:44,993
Ooh, something that will last
until four in the morning.

22
00:03:45,040 --> 00:03:48,396
I'm not staying out till four in the morning.
I have to work tomorrow.

23
00:03:49,200 --> 00:03:52,431
Oh, then wear something orthodox like a suit.

24
00:03:52,480 --> 00:03:53,754
Hey!

25
00:03:54,720 --> 00:03:56,950
Could you answer me just one question?

26
00:03:58,320 --> 00:04:00,390
Is it black tie or isn't it?

27
00:04:00,440 --> 00:04:03,910
- How should I know?
- Well, could you ring and find out?

28
00:04:03,960 --> 00:04:08,397
She'll say some are wearing black tie
and some are not. All very democratic.

29
00:04:08,440 --> 00:04:11,637
And all a big waste of time.

30
00:04:11,680 --> 00:04:14,478
Oh, don't be so stuffy! And don't wear that shin.

31
00:04:14,520 --> 00:04:18,115
Ah, pussycat, I want you to wear
the one I gave you.

32
00:04:18,160 --> 00:04:19,832
Too small.

33
00:04:19,880 --> 00:04:22,110
You must have had a dwarf in mind.

34
00:04:22,160 --> 00:04:24,469
I love you in bright colours!

35
00:04:25,440 --> 00:04:27,158
A peacock.

36
00:04:27,200 --> 00:04:29,191
I love you anyway.

37
00:04:30,240 --> 00:04:32,834
Let's go somewhere on our own tonight.

38
00:04:40,920 --> 00:04:42,717
Gladys will have a fit.

39
00:04:43,760 --> 00:04:45,751
(Sitar music)

40
00:04:51,360 --> 00:04:53,351
(Lively Indian music)

41
00:04:56,400 --> 00:04:59,790
Oh, my darling, wherever you got it, it's divine!

42
00:04:59,840 --> 00:05:03,628
And I'm so glad to see you.
It was sweet of you to come.

43
00:05:03,680 --> 00:05:06,353
Forgive me, will you?
I must get a drink. I'm parched.

44
00:05:06,400 --> 00:05:08,391
I'll see you later.

45
00:05:16,360 --> 00:05:18,476
Zee, my angel!

46
00:05:18,520 --> 00:05:21,239
- Hello, darling.
- How pretty you look.

47
00:05:21,280 --> 00:05:23,236
- Thank you.
- You, too, darling.

48
00:05:23,280 --> 00:05:25,475
You're such a wonderful colour.

49
00:05:25,520 --> 00:05:28,080
Robert told me you'd been to Spain for a week.

50
00:05:28,120 --> 00:05:29,792
When did you get here?

51
00:05:29,840 --> 00:05:31,717
I didn't see you come in.

52
00:05:31,760 --> 00:05:35,116
- About two drinks ago.
- Only two?

53
00:05:36,080 --> 00:05:37,638
Where's Robert?

54
00:05:37,680 --> 00:05:39,398
Oh, out there someplace.

55
00:05:39,440 --> 00:05:41,476
I'm mad about those earrings.

56
00:05:41,520 --> 00:05:44,239
Oh, thanks. They're fake.

57
00:05:44,280 --> 00:05:45,508
Pity.

58
00:05:45,560 --> 00:05:50,873
Yes, well, you know, Robert insisted I leave
the real ones in the shop. Insurance, you know.

59
00:05:50,920 --> 00:05:52,478
So sad.

60
00:05:53,720 --> 00:05:55,836
Listen, if you're really looking for him,

61
00:05:55,880 --> 00:06:00,556
the last time I saw him, he was lurking
behind a potted palm over there.

62
00:06:00,600 --> 00:06:03,910
Well, I must go and find him.
I've something I have to tell him about.

63
00:06:03,960 --> 00:06:05,234
Oh.

64
00:06:11,080 --> 00:06:14,993
I bet you don't know
what the word "byssus" means?

65
00:06:15,040 --> 00:06:17,235
No, I don't, actually, and I don't care.

66
00:06:18,520 --> 00:06:19,794
Beard.

67
00:06:19,840 --> 00:06:24,868
Having long, silky byssus, or beard.

68
00:06:24,920 --> 00:06:26,239
Oh, how exciting.

69
00:06:26,280 --> 00:06:28,236
Now, I wanted your advice.

70
00:06:28,280 --> 00:06:32,831
There's some very interesting African sculptures
come up for auction at Sotheby's.

71
00:06:32,880 --> 00:06:34,598
They're Nigerian, in point of fact.

72
00:06:34,640 --> 00:06:36,153
But I think they'd be divine

73
00:06:36,200 --> 00:06:37,679
for the rose garden.

74
00:06:37,720 --> 00:06:40,359
Yes. Well, we'll go and have a look
one morning next week.

75
00:06:40,400 --> 00:06:43,870
And afterwards,
we'll have a very smart lunch at Burke's.

76
00:06:43,920 --> 00:06:45,831
Are you sure now?

77
00:06:45,880 --> 00:06:47,711
Because last week when you said that,

78
00:06:47,760 --> 00:06:49,591
<i>you forgot and didn't call.</i>

79
00:06:50,560 --> 00:06:54,792
There is a lady behind you
in a silver dress.

80
00:06:54,840 --> 00:06:56,159
Who is she?

81
00:06:56,200 --> 00:06:57,952
No, the other side, the other side.

82
00:06:58,960 --> 00:07:02,316
Oh. That's darling Stella.

83
00:07:02,360 --> 00:07:04,191
Darling Stella?

84
00:07:05,080 --> 00:07:06,718
Can you effect an introduction?

85
00:07:06,760 --> 00:07:08,318
Of course.

86
00:07:08,360 --> 00:07:11,909
But who told me you'd settled down
and were getting eight hours sleep now?

87
00:07:11,960 --> 00:07:15,509
- That was during one of my fits of depression.
- You're a naughty boy.

88
00:07:15,560 --> 00:07:17,118
Very naughty.

89
00:07:17,160 --> 00:07:18,718
Is she a lady of leisure?

90
00:07:18,760 --> 00:07:20,079
No, no, no.

91
00:07:20,120 --> 00:07:21,758
She owns a boutique.

92
00:07:21,800 --> 00:07:24,997
You know, Oriental tat,
but some rather nice frocks.

93
00:07:25,040 --> 00:07:27,156
Er...Stella, dear!

94
00:07:27,200 --> 00:07:29,794
There's someone who doesn't know you.

95
00:07:29,840 --> 00:07:32,479
I thought you said
this was going to be a small gathering?

96
00:07:32,520 --> 00:07:36,149
No, no, darling, not a small gathering,
just small people.

97
00:07:36,200 --> 00:07:37,918
This is Robert.

98
00:07:38,920 --> 00:07:40,433
Robert Blakeley.

99
00:07:44,120 --> 00:07:46,475
Do you need a bodyguard?

100
00:07:48,640 --> 00:07:50,198
No, I don't think so.

101
00:07:52,640 --> 00:07:56,792
Well, now that I've broken the ice, I'll circulate.

102
00:07:56,840 --> 00:07:58,990
And don't forget your promise to call.

103
00:07:59,040 --> 00:08:00,519
Yes, Gladys.

104
00:08:04,880 --> 00:08:06,552
What is this?

105
00:08:06,600 --> 00:08:08,192
It's a Koran case.

106
00:08:10,240 --> 00:08:11,958
It's got a dent in it.

107
00:08:13,160 --> 00:08:14,718
I believe I bit it.

108
00:08:14,760 --> 00:08:16,398
Oh, really?

109
00:08:16,440 --> 00:08:19,000
- Do you bite everything?
- No.

110
00:08:19,040 --> 00:08:20,519
Usually, no.

111
00:08:25,280 --> 00:08:27,077
Are you a lady of leisure?

112
00:08:29,480 --> 00:08:30,993
I'm afraid not.

113
00:08:31,040 --> 00:08:34,828
- Well, what, then?
- I have a shop where I design dresses.

114
00:08:34,880 --> 00:08:36,199
Oh.

115
00:08:36,240 --> 00:08:37,912
Well, you can tell me,

116
00:08:37,960 --> 00:08:42,272
would you say that
I am a particularly well-dressed man?

117
00:08:43,320 --> 00:08:44,309
No.

118
00:08:44,360 --> 00:08:46,191
- <i>Not particularly.</i>
- <i>No?</i>

119
00:08:46,240 --> 00:08:49,550
Don't you think that you should take me in hand?

120
00:08:51,120 --> 00:08:52,838
Clothes are a very personal thing.

121
00:08:52,880 --> 00:08:54,199
<i>I know.</i>

122
00:08:56,320 --> 00:08:57,992
That's what I mean.

123
00:09:01,200 --> 00:09:04,829
- I think she looks like a bag of bones.
- Oh, really?

124
00:09:04,880 --> 00:09:06,871
<i>I think she looks quite nice.</i>

125
00:09:06,920 --> 00:09:09,150
- <i>Do you?</i>
- <i>Who is she?</i>

126
00:09:09,200 --> 00:09:10,679
<i>I have no idea.</i>

127
00:09:11,760 --> 00:09:13,751
I think I'll find out.

128
00:09:13,800 --> 00:09:15,472
Excuse me, love.

129
00:09:15,520 --> 00:09:17,397
Blakeley! I say, Blakeley!

130
00:09:17,440 --> 00:09:19,635
- Your game next.
- Yes, <i>I'll</i> be right there.

131
00:09:20,560 --> 00:09:24,838
Perhaps I could come to your shop
and you could do me some shins.

132
00:09:25,640 --> 00:09:27,631
Most of my designs are for women.

133
00:09:27,680 --> 00:09:29,875
Couldn't you make an exception in my case?

134
00:09:31,360 --> 00:09:32,952
- Perhaps.
- Only perhaps?

135
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:37,198
You would love my family. They're all doctors.

136
00:09:37,240 --> 00:09:39,231
What makes you think I like doctors?

137
00:09:39,280 --> 00:09:42,477
Well, you know, I mean, it just shows.

138
00:09:42,520 --> 00:09:44,033
I can't see it myself.

139
00:09:44,080 --> 00:09:46,230
He's an architect.

140
00:09:46,280 --> 00:09:48,430
He develops properties.

141
00:09:48,480 --> 00:09:50,357
<i>STELLA". I know he's an architect.</i>

142
00:09:50,400 --> 00:09:52,470
- I've heard of him.
- Have you?

143
00:09:53,560 --> 00:09:56,996
Oh, it's not easy being married to a giant.

144
00:09:57,040 --> 00:09:58,996
- Or a dwarf.
(Zee laughs)

145
00:09:59,040 --> 00:10:00,871
It's not easy either way.

146
00:10:00,920 --> 00:10:02,592
- Oh, agony, agony.
- Blakeley!

147
00:10:02,640 --> 00:10:05,677
- If you can't come, we'll play on without you.
- I'll come right now.

148
00:10:05,720 --> 00:10:07,119
Excuse me.

149
00:10:08,320 --> 00:10:11,232
(Laughs) Oh, billiards. He loves his little games.

150
00:10:12,120 --> 00:10:13,678
Do you play?

151
00:10:13,720 --> 00:10:15,392
I'm afraid not.

152
00:10:16,360 --> 00:10:17,952
Nor do I.

153
00:10:19,280 --> 00:10:21,077
Ping pong is my sport.

154
00:10:21,120 --> 00:10:23,350
Robert says because it's more aggressive.

155
00:10:23,400 --> 00:10:25,277
Would you like to go watch them?

156
00:10:25,320 --> 00:10:27,311
Fine, if you like.

157
00:10:29,040 --> 00:10:30,439
MAN; Oh!

158
00:10:44,840 --> 00:10:46,193
Good shot.

159
00:10:46,240 --> 00:10:47,992
I really cannot stand this room.

160
00:10:50,280 --> 00:10:52,191
It gives me the creeps.

161
00:10:56,200 --> 00:10:59,988
Have you ever noticed
how Gladys always has one of everything?

162
00:11:00,040 --> 00:11:02,713
One actor, one painter, one faith healer.

163
00:11:02,760 --> 00:11:06,673
- But we all come and guzzle her champagne.
- Ha, ha!

164
00:11:06,720 --> 00:11:09,280
She guzzles out of a silver mug.

165
00:11:09,320 --> 00:11:10,594
Crafty.

166
00:11:10,640 --> 00:11:13,996
You know, you can't get through to her
after 11 in the morning.

167
00:11:14,040 --> 00:11:15,871
All her words begin to go son of...

168
00:11:15,920 --> 00:11:18,832
"Robert, daaarling..."

169
00:11:18,880 --> 00:11:23,510
Do you know she asks Robert
his advice about everything?

170
00:11:23,560 --> 00:11:26,950
<i>Even having her face lifted,
she asked his advice.</i>

171
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:31,436
- It'll be my turn soon for that.
- (Laughs)

172
00:11:31,480 --> 00:11:33,232
Well, now you know who to ask.

173
00:11:34,080 --> 00:11:35,149
Me.

174
00:11:35,200 --> 00:11:37,839
<i>Oh, but I like your face.</i>

175
00:11:39,040 --> 00:11:40,951
Your shadows.

176
00:11:42,600 --> 00:11:43,953
Marvelous.

177
00:11:49,360 --> 00:11:51,749
We should have brought our embroidery.

178
00:12:09,200 --> 00:12:12,510
<i>I hope he doesn't lose, or I'll get the blame.</i>

179
00:12:12,560 --> 00:12:14,312
He's a bad loser.

180
00:12:14,360 --> 00:12:16,237
<i>He's a miser,</i> too.

181
00:12:16,280 --> 00:12:21,638
Do you know that he didn't even buy me
my wedding ring? He borrowed his sister's.

182
00:12:21,680 --> 00:12:24,911
We got the weirdest wedding presents.
Do you know what one of them was?

183
00:12:24,960 --> 00:12:27,793
A collapsible leather wastepaper basket.

184
00:12:28,880 --> 00:12:30,552
<i>Yucky</i> green leather.

185
00:12:33,480 --> 00:12:36,392
Er...did you get nice wedding presents?

186
00:12:38,320 --> 00:12:40,880
- I eloped.
- Oh, good for you.

187
00:12:42,360 --> 00:12:43,793
Where is he?

188
00:12:44,600 --> 00:12:46,079
He's in the country.

189
00:12:46,120 --> 00:12:47,712
Any children?

190
00:12:47,760 --> 00:12:49,557
Yes. Two boys.

191
00:12:49,600 --> 00:12:51,875
Oh, how charming.

192
00:12:51,920 --> 00:12:56,232
<i>GLADYS:
Oh, there you are, my darlings!</i>

193
00:12:56,280 --> 00:12:58,510
How nice to see you're getting along.

194
00:12:58,560 --> 00:13:00,039
Yes, isn't it?

195
00:13:00,080 --> 00:13:02,514
<i>GLADYS'.
You know, this room...</i>

196
00:13:02,560 --> 00:13:04,915
<i>has always had a special quality for me.</i>

197
00:13:06,360 --> 00:13:08,954
<i>It's a man's room,</i>

198
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:11,560
something they don't build into houses
any more.

199
00:13:11,600 --> 00:13:13,636
Yes, thank God.

200
00:13:24,720 --> 00:13:26,517
What did you say?

201
00:13:26,560 --> 00:13:28,994
Oh, I was just telling her about myself.

202
00:13:31,360 --> 00:13:33,351
You know, she told me

203
00:13:33,400 --> 00:13:37,154
she's prone to weeping
if anything nice happens to her.

204
00:13:38,080 --> 00:13:40,548
Yuck, yuck!

205
00:13:54,720 --> 00:13:56,278
(Knocks)

206
00:13:56,320 --> 00:13:57,639
Stella?

207
00:13:58,920 --> 00:14:00,911
- Are you all right?
- Yes.

208
00:14:02,160 --> 00:14:03,912
Open the door, then.

209
00:14:07,520 --> 00:14:08,839
What's upset you?

210
00:14:10,480 --> 00:14:12,869
Nothing. Really.

211
00:14:14,480 --> 00:14:17,916
If I call, will you have dinner with me?

212
00:14:19,440 --> 00:14:21,351
ZEE: Robert!

213
00:14:21,400 --> 00:14:23,391
<i>We're all going dancing!</i>

214
00:14:23,440 --> 00:14:25,476
I'm not going dancing, I'm going home.

215
00:14:25,520 --> 00:14:27,078
<i>Oh, no!</i>

216
00:14:27,120 --> 00:14:30,510
- <i>Me want my Bobby in my arms...</i>
- I'll call <i>you tomorrow.</i>

217
00:14:31,880 --> 00:14:33,552
<i>Robert!</i>

218
00:14:33,600 --> 00:14:35,795
- Oh!
- All right, I'm coming!

219
00:14:35,840 --> 00:14:39,071
(Sings drunkenly) Bobby, Bobby, Bobby...
Dov'é, dov'é, dove?

220
00:14:39,120 --> 00:14:40,872
Bugger

221
00:14:40,920 --> 00:14:43,195
- (Squeals)
- You can out the little girl crap

222
00:14:43,240 --> 00:14:45,549
because you're not persuading me
to do anything!

223
00:14:45,600 --> 00:14:49,036
You're not persuading me to do anything!
We are not going dancing...

224
00:14:50,120 --> 00:14:51,712
- Thank you, sir.
- Thank you.

225
00:14:51,760 --> 00:14:53,398
It's getting late.

226
00:14:55,080 --> 00:14:56,559
You see that?

227
00:14:56,600 --> 00:15:01,594
That is the first time in years that I've worn
a watch. That's what you've done to me.

228
00:15:01,640 --> 00:15:04,632
You've made me count the minutes.

229
00:15:04,680 --> 00:15:07,274
I've waited all day to see you.

230
00:15:09,640 --> 00:15:11,596
What do you want to eat?

231
00:15:13,760 --> 00:15:16,513
I feel I ought to warn you - I'm expensive.

232
00:15:16,560 --> 00:15:19,836
I only eat the choicest things,
apart from cabbage.

233
00:15:19,880 --> 00:15:23,077
Oh, really? Zee likes that, too, late at night.

234
00:15:23,120 --> 00:15:25,111
I knew we had something in common.

235
00:15:26,480 --> 00:15:28,311
Is there anything else?

236
00:15:30,480 --> 00:15:32,277
I don't know that yet, do I?

237
00:15:36,960 --> 00:15:40,157
People never want to admit they were in love
once it's over.

238
00:15:41,720 --> 00:15:43,836
How they sat on a bench and waited.

239
00:15:44,880 --> 00:15:46,552
Or danced all night.

240
00:15:47,800 --> 00:15:49,518
Or went for a walk in the frost.

241
00:15:50,200 --> 00:15:51,792
Blew on someone's fingers.

242
00:15:52,960 --> 00:15:55,758
Everyone has two types,

243
00:15:55,800 --> 00:15:58,268
and one is true and one is false.

244
00:15:58,320 --> 00:16:00,436
How can you tell?

245
00:16:00,480 --> 00:16:02,277
You can tell...

246
00:16:02,320 --> 00:16:04,197
by the skin...

247
00:16:05,960 --> 00:16:07,678
...and by the touch.

248
00:16:10,760 --> 00:16:12,637
And by the eyes -

249
00:16:13,440 --> 00:16:15,237
the windows of the soul.

250
00:16:15,280 --> 00:16:16,793
(Laughs)

251
00:16:18,960 --> 00:16:21,520
Come on. Let's go.

252
00:16:23,960 --> 00:16:25,598
- Hello, Robert.
- Hello.

253
00:16:25,640 --> 00:16:27,119
(Car horn)

254
00:16:27,160 --> 00:16:28,798
A hummingbird.

255
00:16:28,840 --> 00:16:30,637
- A pretty one.
- Yeah.

256
00:16:30,680 --> 00:16:32,716
Well, wrap yourself up. It's very cold.

257
00:16:33,920 --> 00:16:36,593
Would you like to be kissed...there?

258
00:16:36,640 --> 00:16:38,039
No.

259
00:16:38,080 --> 00:16:39,752
- There?
- Uh-uh.

260
00:16:40,760 --> 00:16:42,432
- There?
