00:30:31,600 --> 00:30:34,831
I took it into school
and I showed it to all the other boys.

509
00:30:35,760 --> 00:30:38,354
And none of them
ever called me Muggins again.

510
00:30:38,400 --> 00:30:39,435
<i>Well.</i> ..

511
00:30:39,480 --> 00:30:41,948
- I think you should go to bed. Come on.
- Oh, no!

512
00:30:42,000 --> 00:30:44,992
- Come on! School tomorrow.
- Come off it!

513
00:30:45,040 --> 00:30:47,031
Say good night to Mr Blakeley.

514
00:30:47,080 --> 00:30:48,877
- Good night, Sean.
- Sean!

515
00:30:48,920 --> 00:30:50,797
- Good night.
- Good night, Oscar.

516
00:30:50,840 --> 00:30:53,798
- Now, up. I won't be long.
- Come on, Oscar.

517
00:30:53,840 --> 00:30:56,308
Brush your teeth. Night.
- OK Good night Mummy.

518
00:30:56,360 --> 00:30:58,316
- Night.
- Don '1' be long.

519
00:31:03,520 --> 00:31:05,431
Will you sleep?

520
00:31:05,480 --> 00:31:07,198
I hope so.

521
00:31:08,360 --> 00:31:10,351
But I doubt it.

522
00:31:12,720 --> 00:31:14,676
I hope you enjoyed my family.

523
00:31:16,440 --> 00:31:19,113
- I'm sorry it wasn't much of an evening.
- Don't be sorry.

524
00:31:20,200 --> 00:31:22,555
I think your boys are charming little men.

525
00:31:34,560 --> 00:31:36,232
Where will you go now?

526
00:31:36,280 --> 00:31:38,157
Home, I suppose.

527
00:31:38,200 --> 00:31:40,077
When is she coming back?

528
00:31:40,120 --> 00:31:41,712
I don't know.

529
00:31:41,760 --> 00:31:43,671
She'll be away for a few days.

530
00:31:45,400 --> 00:31:46,958
Tomorrow night,

531
00:31:47,000 --> 00:31:49,355
my housekeeper will cook us dinner.

532
00:31:51,080 --> 00:31:54,072
And we'll be alone, the two of us, all right?

533
00:32:04,040 --> 00:32:05,712
You must go.

534
00:32:05,760 --> 00:32:07,239
Must I?

535
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:09,911
- Must I?
- Yes.

536
00:32:18,320 --> 00:32:20,231
- Good night.
- Good night.

537
00:32:40,520 --> 00:32:42,158
(Clears throat)

538
00:32:42,200 --> 00:32:44,998
Say whatever it is you have come to say.

539
00:32:45,040 --> 00:32:47,474
Mrs Blakeley is downstairs.

540
00:32:47,520 --> 00:32:50,751
- What?
- Your wife is downstairs.

541
00:32:50,800 --> 00:32:52,950
My what is where?

542
00:32:53,000 --> 00:32:55,230
Why the hell didn't you tell me before?

543
00:32:55,280 --> 00:32:57,475
<i>You said you didn't want to be disturbed.</i>

544
00:32:57,520 --> 00:32:59,829
- What time is it?
- 6:30.

545
00:32:59,880 --> 00:33:02,713
She got here before six.
She insisted I came to tell you.

546
00:33:02,760 --> 00:33:06,150
Well, tell her I'm not here.
Tell her... Tell her I've gone away.

547
00:33:06,200 --> 00:33:07,997
<i>Tell her any damn thing!</i>

548
00:33:08,040 --> 00:33:11,555
I've already told her you were working
and didn't want to be disturbed.

549
00:33:11,600 --> 00:33:13,318
You bungle everything, don't you?

550
00:33:13,360 --> 00:33:16,591
<i>Well, would you like to tell her
that you were misinformed?</i>

551
00:33:16,640 --> 00:33:18,710
- No.
- No.

552
00:33:18,760 --> 00:33:21,194
I thought you wouldn't. Damn it.

553
00:33:21,240 --> 00:33:25,438
Well, would you do me one favour
and get your glasses repaired?

554
00:33:25,480 --> 00:33:27,630
They're beginning to get on my nerves.

555
00:33:27,680 --> 00:33:29,477
Both them and you!

556
00:33:29,520 --> 00:33:32,478
Get a pair on the bloody National Health!

557
00:33:33,800 --> 00:33:35,791
<i>Do you think I've got money to burn</i>

558
00:33:35,840 --> 00:33:38,274
while you go flying off to Spain for one night?

559
00:33:38,320 --> 00:33:41,392
- Well, it was cold and it was wet.
- Well, if...

560
00:33:41,440 --> 00:33:43,317
ZEE: What the hell did you expect me to do?

561
00:33:43,360 --> 00:33:45,476
- Just sit there and...
- No.

562
00:33:45,520 --> 00:33:47,715
...stare out of the window and look at the rain?

563
00:33:47,760 --> 00:33:50,149
No, I expected you to have some sense,
that's all.

564
00:33:50,200 --> 00:33:51,474
Oh!

565
00:33:51,520 --> 00:33:54,193
You must have had a rough day today.

566
00:33:54,240 --> 00:33:55,798
No, I had a very good day.

567
00:33:55,840 --> 00:33:57,193
<i>Did you?</i>

568
00:33:57,240 --> 00:34:01,233
<i>I tried to call you last night
to say! was sorry, but...</i>

569
00:34:02,240 --> 00:34:04,231
.there was no answer.

570
00:34:04,280 --> 00:34:05,838
I was out.

571
00:34:10,560 --> 00:34:12,437
Where do you want to eat?

572
00:34:13,640 --> 00:34:15,392
Why, home, darling.

573
00:34:15,440 --> 00:34:17,874
Home sweet home.

574
00:34:19,200 --> 00:34:21,668
I don't think there's a lot to eat at home.

575
00:34:21,720 --> 00:34:23,472
Oh, we'll find something.

576
00:34:25,320 --> 00:34:26,958
We could go over to Gladys's.

577
00:34:27,000 --> 00:34:29,195
<i>She's having people to dinner.</i>

578
00:34:29,240 --> 00:34:31,549
I wouldn't dream of that, darling.

579
00:34:32,440 --> 00:34:35,796
I just want to go home with you and relax.

580
00:34:38,560 --> 00:34:40,471
Look...

581
00:34:40,520 --> 00:34:44,718
- I think there's something I should tell you.
- Oh, later, darling, when we're home.

582
00:34:44,760 --> 00:34:46,830
I'm too tired to listen even.

583
00:34:50,200 --> 00:34:51,599
(Tires screech)

584
00:34:51,640 --> 00:34:53,517
(Car horns)

585
00:34:53,560 --> 00:34:55,551
(Rock music on stereo)

586
00:35:08,720 --> 00:35:11,188
Oh, intimate.

587
00:35:11,240 --> 00:35:13,071
Hors doeuvres.

588
00:35:13,120 --> 00:35:15,076
How lovely!

589
00:35:15,120 --> 00:35:17,111
What are we having?

590
00:35:17,160 --> 00:35:20,118
Or should I say, who are we having?

591
00:35:21,840 --> 00:35:24,832
And a note from our trusted housekeeper.

592
00:35:26,240 --> 00:35:27,912
"Dear Sir Robert..."

593
00:35:27,960 --> 00:35:29,393
Sir?

594
00:35:29,440 --> 00:35:31,715
<i>You haven't been knighted yet, sweetie.</i>

595
00:35:32,520 --> 00:35:35,830
"The joint...is in the oven...

596
00:35:36,840 --> 00:35:38,831
...and should be ready at 8:30.

597
00:35:39,720 --> 00:35:42,632
Hope everything is to your satisfaction.

598
00:35:42,680 --> 00:35:44,671
Yours truly, Bea Donovan."

599
00:35:47,720 --> 00:35:52,236
Our ex-housekeeper hopes
everything is to your satisfaction.

600
00:35:53,760 --> 00:35:56,797
Quite a wit, our Mrs Thing,
when she puts pen to paper.

601
00:35:57,880 --> 00:35:59,757
I always was warned off the Irish.

602
00:35:59,800 --> 00:36:01,119
Really?

603
00:36:02,120 --> 00:36:04,111
They speak very well of you.

604
00:36:09,840 --> 00:36:11,353
(Doorbell)

605
00:36:11,400 --> 00:36:13,152
Ha-ha! Ho-ho!

606
00:36:13,200 --> 00:36:15,475
Our mystery caller.

607
00:36:15,520 --> 00:36:17,909
It's no mystery to me, baby.

608
00:36:19,600 --> 00:36:21,158
Bob, seriously,

609
00:36:21,200 --> 00:36:22,758
would you...

610
00:36:22,800 --> 00:36:25,394
would you like me to make myself scarce?

611
00:36:32,880 --> 00:36:34,438
(Doorbell)

612
00:36:36,720 --> 00:36:41,919
(Gasps) Why, if it isn't darling Stella!

613
00:36:41,960 --> 00:36:44,190
<i>What a lovely surprise.</i>

614
00:36:44,240 --> 00:36:47,277
<i>Come in, come in, come in.
Let me take your cloak.</i>

615
00:36:48,400 --> 00:36:50,709
And what is that?

616
00:36:51,600 --> 00:36:54,034
- Our first course.
- Ah!

617
00:36:56,120 --> 00:36:57,439
Pate!

618
00:36:57,480 --> 00:37:00,472
Did you make it yourself?
I bet you did, didn't you?

619
00:37:00,520 --> 00:37:02,272
- Yes.
- Ah, you see.

620
00:37:02,320 --> 00:37:06,791
<i>I told you she would know how to cook.
I just knew it.</i>

621
00:37:07,480 --> 00:37:10,472
Did you take quantities of belly of pork and veal

622
00:37:10,520 --> 00:37:13,193
and oddments from wild duck and pheasant,

623
00:37:13,240 --> 00:37:16,391
and dry white wine and juniper berries and...

624
00:37:17,400 --> 00:37:20,597
...mmm, carcasses and all that?

625
00:37:20,640 --> 00:37:22,039
Zee.

626
00:37:22,080 --> 00:37:23,911
Will you shut up?

627
00:37:25,040 --> 00:37:27,634
Well, I wasn't being vicious, was I?

628
00:37:28,560 --> 00:37:31,120
I don't know. Were you?

629
00:37:31,160 --> 00:37:32,479
<i>Me?</i>

630
00:37:34,240 --> 00:37:36,151
Would you like a Martini?

631
00:37:36,200 --> 00:37:38,156
Make the lady some Martini, booby.

632
00:37:39,240 --> 00:37:41,993
<i>Your hands are cold.</i>

633
00:37:42,040 --> 00:37:44,270
Hard to get a taxi.
They'd gone home to their tea.

634
00:37:44,320 --> 00:37:46,880
- Pigs.
- He tried to charge me double.

635
00:37:46,920 --> 00:37:49,718
- <i>He thought! was a Norwegian.</i>
- <i>Are you, Stella?</i>

636
00:37:50,560 --> 00:37:52,437
Of course not!

637
00:37:52,480 --> 00:37:55,790
She's a Celt, from the top 0' the mornin' country.

638
00:37:55,840 --> 00:37:58,070
Actually, I have Spanish blood.

639
00:37:58,120 --> 00:38:00,588
A-ha! Toro!

640
00:38:04,840 --> 00:38:06,068
Ta.

641
00:38:06,120 --> 00:38:07,633
Thank you.

642
00:38:09,280 --> 00:38:10,633
Cheers.

643
00:38:21,120 --> 00:38:22,269
Oh...

644
00:38:23,080 --> 00:38:26,914
Er..Robert collects fish.

645
00:38:26,960 --> 00:38:29,190
<i>He has a whole collection.</i>

646
00:38:29,240 --> 00:38:30,958
<i>There</i> are...

647
00:38:31,000 --> 00:38:34,072
puffers and walking fish

648
00:38:34,120 --> 00:38:36,680
and flying fish and kissing fish

649
00:38:36,720 --> 00:38:39,439
and er. . .scavengers

650
00:38:39,480 --> 00:38:42,552
<i>and barracuda and...</i>

651
00:38:43,800 --> 00:38:45,074
...piranha.

652
00:38:45,120 --> 00:38:47,554
<i>You know, they eat other fish</i>

653
00:38:47,600 --> 00:38:50,797
and...cows and things like that.

654
00:38:50,840 --> 00:38:52,671
They're Robert's favourite fish.

655
00:38:52,720 --> 00:38:55,234
He never said they were his favourite.

656
00:38:55,280 --> 00:38:56,508
<i>(Laughs)</i>

657
00:38:56,560 --> 00:38:58,471
Robert loves the sea.

658
00:38:58,520 --> 00:39:00,192
He never said he loved the sea either.

659
00:39:01,440 --> 00:39:03,431
So he doesn't love the sea.

660
00:39:03,480 --> 00:39:07,234
And what did you do today?
Did you have some lovely fittings?

661
00:39:07,280 --> 00:39:08,838
I had a lovely day.

662
00:39:08,880 --> 00:39:10,791
I didn't go near the shop.

663
00:39:10,840 --> 00:39:12,796
<i>My boys were going back to school.</i>

664
00:39:13,680 --> 00:39:16,148
- <i>How old are they?</i>
- <i>Nine. They're twins.</i>

665
00:39:17,880 --> 00:39:19,757
Twins!

666
00:39:19,800 --> 00:39:22,234
Oh, you didn't tell me!

667
00:39:22,280 --> 00:39:23,838
Did you breast-feed them?

668
00:39:23,880 --> 00:39:27,919
<i>I sat next to a man at dinner one night</i>

669
00:39:27,960 --> 00:39:30,190
whose wife had just given birth to twins.

670
00:39:30,240 --> 00:39:32,117
And he said, "You haven't lived

671
00:39:32,160 --> 00:39:35,277
until you have seen a woman breast-feed twins."

672
00:39:35,320 --> 00:39:38,949
Evidently,
his wife would lie sprawled on the bed,

673
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:41,992
a tit in either direction,

674
00:39:42,040 --> 00:39:44,600
and it was just evidently fantastic.

675
00:39:44,640 --> 00:39:46,392
I didn't have enough milk.

676
00:39:47,320 --> 00:39:48,673
Oh.

677
00:39:50,440 --> 00:39:52,715
You know, I read in the papers once

678
00:39:52,760 --> 00:39:56,753
about a sheepdog,
I think it was a Pyrenees sheepdog,

679
00:39:56,800 --> 00:39:59,314
that had 14 puppies

680
00:39:59,360 --> 00:40:01,635
and only 12 tits.

681
00:40:02,600 --> 00:40:04,477
Isn't nature cruel?

682
00:40:04,520 --> 00:40:07,080
12 out of 14's not so cruel.

683
00:40:08,120 --> 00:40:11,192
- The twins have survived, anyway.
- Oh, that's nice.

684
00:40:11,240 --> 00:40:12,958
I wish I'd met them.

685
00:40:13,000 --> 00:40:16,072
I love little boys and little girls.

686
00:40:16,120 --> 00:40:19,795
Wouldn't you like to chew on a bone
or a piece of gristle?

687
00:40:20,560 --> 00:40:22,676
What a good idea!

688
00:40:22,720 --> 00:40:26,952
<i>Why don't you take us
to our favourite restaurant, huh?</i>

689
00:40:27,000 --> 00:40:30,151
With people around,
it might help fill in some of the gaps.

690
00:40:31,280 --> 00:40:33,191
I'll go get my clobber, OK?

691
00:40:38,280 --> 00:40:39,793
Gaps?

692
00:40:40,600 --> 00:40:42,511
I didn't notice any gaps.

693
00:40:42,560 --> 00:40:44,118
Did you?

694
00:40:47,240 --> 00:40:48,832
Chasms.

695
00:40:53,080 --> 00:40:55,435
Well, I'm ready.

696
00:40:56,480 --> 00:40:59,711
<i>Oh, er...Bobby, darling,
would you douse the fire?</i>

697
00:40:59,760 --> 00:41:02,320
We do have our little economies.

698
00:41:13,640 --> 00:41:15,631
<i>ZEE. It wasn't as in as it is now.</i>

699
00:41:15,680 --> 00:41:19,275
You know, we used to have
our correspondence addressed here.

700
00:41:20,200 --> 00:41:23,431
One day at lunchtime,
I found a pearl in my oyster.

701
00:41:23,480 --> 00:41:26,153
<i>It was just a grimy little pearl, but still a pearl.</i>

702
00:41:26,200 --> 00:41:27,599
(Clears throat)

703
00:41:27,640 --> 00:41:30,757
- Ah, Signore, come sta?
- Benissimo, Signora.

704
00:41:32,040 --> 00:41:34,998
He comes from Parma.
You know, where the violets grow.

705
00:41:35,040 --> 00:41:36,678
And the ham.

706
00:41:36,720 --> 00:41:38,119
(Laughs)

707
00:41:39,120 --> 00:41:40,872
Did the boys go back today?

708
00:41:42,240 --> 00:41:43,673
Reluctantly.

709
00:41:43,720 --> 00:41:45,631
I wish I'd been with you to see them off.

710
00:41:45,680 --> 00:41:48,274
I bet neither one of you
know about Parma violets.

711
00:41:48,320 --> 00:41:52,598
Even if we did, we wouldn't deprive you
of the pleasure of telling us.

712
00:41:54,920 --> 00:41:57,798
Well, they're very delicate,

713
00:41:57,840 --> 00:42:01,435
<i>and they're what people give
when they want to give something really special.</i>

714
00:42:02,640 --> 00:42:04,358
When they're in love...

715
00:42:04,400 --> 00:42:06,675
- or someone dies...
(Waiter clears throat)

716
00:42:06,720 --> 00:42:09,951
Ah, yes, now let me see. What shall we have?

717
00:42:11,520 --> 00:42:13,590
I think we should have some pasta to start

718
00:42:13,640 --> 00:42:16,632
<i>How about cannelloni? I adore cannelloni.</i>

719
00:42:16,680 --> 00:42:18,875
Then we should have - let me see...

720
00:42:19,720 --> 00:42:21,358
Chicken cacciatore, how's that?

721
00:42:21,400 --> 00:42:22,913
Sounds fine.

722
00:42:22,960 --> 00:42:24,439
And for the signore?

723
00:42:26,960 --> 00:42:28,598
Melon and Dover sole.

724
00:42:28,640 --> 00:42:30,756
Melon and Dover sole!

725
00:42:31,760 --> 00:42:34,149
I think he's frightened of getting an ulcer.

726
00:42:34,200 --> 00:42:38,512
- Everyone seems to have them today.
- It wouldn't surprise me, the way he eats.

727
00:42:38,560 --> 00:42:40,232
He has nothing but fry-ups -

728
00:42:40,280 --> 00:42:44,671
bacon, fried sausages, fried bread,
fried tomatoes, fried eggs...

729
00:42:44,720 --> 00:42:46,312
<i>Don't you try and dissuade him?</i>

730
00:42:46,360 --> 00:42:48,920
- I mean, with your own cooking?
- Web', sure!

731
00:42:48,960 --> 00:42:51,554
Sure. But, you know, what can I do?

732
00:42:52,600 --> 00:42:54,477
It's his background, really.

733
00:42:54,520 --> 00:42:56,590
<i>How can you fight it?</i>

734
00:42:56,640 --> 00:42:59,757
I mean, from what he tells me,
that's what they lived on.

735
00:42:59,800 --> 00:43:03,918
<i>When it wasn't bread and dripping,
it was those eternal fry-ups.</i>

736
00:43:04,720 --> 00:43:07,792
<i>We fried to put him on a diet so many times,
We lost count.</i>

737
00:43:07,840 --> 00:43:10,149
I'm sure,
when I feed him a proper meal at home,

738
00:43:10,200 --> 00:43:12,839
he just goes straight out
and has one of those huge lunches

739
00:43:12,880 --> 00:43:15,394
<i>with sausages and chips and all the rest of it.</i>

740
00:43:15,440 --> 00:43:19,149
- <i>Excuse me.</i>
- <i>If he wants to get fat and ruin his constitution</i>

741
00:43:19,200 --> 00:43:21,760
<i>and get a pot belly, well, let him.</i>

742
00:43:21,800 --> 00:43:24,234
<i>I mean, there's nothing I can do about it,
is there?</i>

743
00:43:24,280 --> 00:43:27,590
If somebody has decided to do something,

744
00:43:27,640 --> 00:43:29,631
they can't be stopped.

745
00:43:29,680 --> 00:43:31,636
Can they?

746
00:43:31,720 --> 00:43:33,551
(Phone rings)

747
00:43:33,600 --> 00:43:38,230
Gino, would you give this to my wife
and tell her, "Buonanotte"?

748
00:43:38,280 --> 00:43:39,713
Yes, signore.

749
00:43:39,760 --> 00:43:41,318
Oh, allow me, sir.

750
00:43:45,640 --> 00:43:48,359
ZEE: It's the most marvelous material,
divine colour...

751
00:43:48,400 --> 00:43:50,356
- Sousa, Signora.
- Thank you.

752
00:43:53,360 --> 00:43:55,191
Why, that bastard!

753
00:43:55,240 --> 00:43:57,037
He's run out on us.

754
00:43:57,080 --> 00:43:59,036
That dirty coward!

755
00:43:59,080 --> 00:44:02,072
If that isn't just like a man, to run out.

756
00:44:04,320 --> 00:44:06,151
Are you terribly upset?

757
00:44:06,200 --> 00:44:07,474
(Giggles)

758
00:44:09,680 --> 00:44:11,193
Not particularly.

759
00:44:11,880 --> 00:44:13,791
Do you want to have a good cry?

760
00:44:13,840 --> 00:44:15,671
